1
00:00:01,312 --> 00:00:27,792
samantacchakavalesu attaragacchantu devata sadhammamunirajasasunantusagamokadam dhammasavanakalo ayambhadantam dhammasavanakalo ayambhadantam dhammasavanakalo ayambhadantam

2
00:00:36,868 --> 00:00:38,210
Many thanks for the invitation.

3
00:00:41,454 --> 00:00:43,597
I was born in Manchester.

4
00:00:44,079 --> 00:00:45,561
Not born in Manchester, brought up in Manchester.

5
00:00:45,661 --> 00:00:46,262
I'm the real thing.

6
00:00:47,804 --> 00:00:51,408
Perfectly Northern.

7
00:00:51,429 --> 00:00:58,838
So when I was coming up, I asked Dr. Farrokh Gamage what I should talk about.

8
00:00:58,859 --> 00:01:05,408
He suggested I talk about rituals, the purpose of rituals, and

9
00:01:07,159 --> 00:01:14,730
ceremonies that we have in various types of Buddhisms, but specifically in Theravada Buddhism, and, you know, what their role is.

10
00:01:19,876 --> 00:01:25,944
If we go back to the Buddha himself, he came out of a very ritualistic religion.

11
00:01:27,459 --> 00:01:36,649
Hinduism at that time, it's now called Hinduism because the British called it Hindu, because it was to do with the name of India.

12
00:01:37,469 --> 00:01:47,219
They themselves would have called it Dhamma, the truth, just a law, which became obviously a word that the Buddha himself used, the Dhamma.

13
00:01:47,239 --> 00:01:54,766
And as I'm sure you know, it was led by the Brahmin caste, and it was really based around a whole system of rituals,

14
00:01:55,304 --> 00:02:01,331
which were to do with appeasing gods and to do with getting power.

15
00:02:02,653 --> 00:02:14,288
It first of all began, as all early religion, the idea was that there were all these gods who ruled, nature gods, you know, god of fire, god of thunder, same as in Greek mythology.

16
00:02:15,389 --> 00:02:19,294
And the idea was that you offered these gods something and they did something for you.

17
00:02:20,115 --> 00:02:23,860
This became slightly corrupted as time went on because we understood that

18
00:02:24,110 --> 00:02:26,995
There came a time, if you did offer something to a god, he couldn't refuse.

19
00:02:28,456 --> 00:02:35,026
So therefore, huge sacrifices were made, especially of, the worst one was the horse sacrifice.

20
00:02:35,187 --> 00:02:39,174
Thousands of horses were sacrificed so they'd benefit the kingdom.

21
00:02:39,875 --> 00:02:46,185
And it was understood that once you made this great sacrifice, whatever you demanded from the gods would be given, you see.

22
00:02:47,954 --> 00:02:51,399
There were all sorts of varied rituals and ceremonies.

23
00:02:51,459 --> 00:03:01,354
Like, for instance, as a child he watched his father conducting the plowing ceremony which opened the season for seeding the crops and things like that.

24
00:03:02,175 --> 00:03:10,407
So the Buddha grew up in a society which was just replete with all sorts of ceremonies and rituals, empowering rituals.

25
00:03:11,930 --> 00:03:16,897
And by the time he himself, when he became enlightened,

26
00:03:17,418 --> 00:03:45,719
Now really, I don't think, and I stand corrected, apart from the rituals that he established for the order, which was to do basically with coming together once every two weeks to confess to each other any transgressions of the rules, and then to go through the actual ceremony of, call it a ceremony, of reading, reciting the rules,

27
00:03:46,342 --> 00:04:13,294
apart from that and of course the ordination ceremony and one or two little ceremonies like beginning the rainy season where monks have to stay in a monastery things like that he instituted very little rituals or ceremonies as we would recognize them in Buddhism as we find it in various countries now and he seems not to have been at all interested in

28
00:04:14,590 --> 00:04:23,764
other rituals which would have been part and parcel of any Indian life, which, you know, birth rituals, marriage rituals, and death rituals.

29
00:04:24,524 --> 00:04:29,273
There's nothing in the scriptures to suggest that he attended such things or took part in such things.

30
00:04:29,954 --> 00:04:36,202
And the general understanding was that the religion of the time took care of that.

31
00:04:36,803 --> 00:04:38,607
And his own focus was basically

32
00:04:38,940 --> 00:04:49,620
on getting people to begin to move towards what he had discovered, the enlightenment, the end of suffering.

33
00:04:49,641 --> 00:04:59,059
So it's against that background that we have to think of modern rituals and modern things that we'd like just now, all this chanting that we've done.

34
00:05:00,180 --> 00:05:02,264
Then towards the end of his life,

35
00:05:03,173 --> 00:05:15,173
He suggests that the four main places to do with his life's journey be a place where people could come and reflect on the teaching and pay homage.

36
00:05:15,194 --> 00:05:25,992
The main one, of course, is this huge stupa that was built in Kusinara, and his birthplace, and where he became enlightened, Bodh Gaya.

37
00:05:26,478 --> 00:05:37,175
And all these places these days now, I believe, are huge tourist attractions and places of ceremony and worship by Buddhist followers from all around the world.

38
00:05:37,755 --> 00:05:41,540
Huge temples, especially the Japanese, I believe, have built great big beautiful temples.

39
00:05:42,562 --> 00:05:44,305
Hotels, of course.

40
00:05:44,326 --> 00:05:46,588
Casinos.

41
00:05:46,608 --> 00:05:51,557
So, how is it then that various rituals began to grow up?

42
00:05:52,279 --> 00:06:14,964
Well, even there, with the establishment of these four places, places where people could go to reflect upon the teaching of the Buddha and pay homage, there's an understanding by the Buddha that once he's gone, people will need some sort of place, some sort of way of remembering his presence.

43
00:06:14,985 --> 00:06:16,887
Now, if you think, you know,

44
00:06:18,081 --> 00:06:19,846
At the time of the Buddha, he was always there.

45
00:06:19,886 --> 00:06:23,192
It wasn't necessary to have anything to remember him by.

46
00:06:23,213 --> 00:06:28,865
It wasn't necessary to have a ritual to conjure up some sort of relationship with him.

47
00:06:28,925 --> 00:06:29,848
He was always there.

48
00:06:30,028 --> 00:06:36,242
You could seek him out, find him, and ask your questions and get the direction you wanted.

49
00:06:36,778 --> 00:06:52,156
When that went, we can see from even Ananda's question to him, you know, who will you lead to guide us now, you see, now that you're dying, you've set up the order, who will you lead as the next leader of the Sangha, next leader of the Buddhist community?

50
00:06:52,817 --> 00:07:02,247
And he says, well, leave anybody, see, throws poor Ananda off a bit, and he says, what I'm leaving you is the teaching that I've given, the Dhamma,

51
00:07:02,901 --> 00:07:18,312
and you yourself you yourself must be your own refuge you know no point in taking refuge in me I'm not here anymore and so he threw it back to Ananda and he throws it back to us personally so we ourselves must become our own refuge

52
00:07:19,404 --> 00:07:34,122
So now, if we look at our own practices, especially in the Theravada vision, as I say, we can begin to see where certain rites and rituals might be just part and parcel of any spiritual path.

53
00:07:35,764 --> 00:07:45,074
Now, there will always be those people who can give up everything, go and live in

54
00:07:45,442 --> 00:07:57,072
in the mobile, somewhere up on the peak district, and make it all the way to enlightenment, and with no need for anything, apart from just a place to sit and meditate.

55
00:07:58,156 --> 00:08:00,802
But they're very rare, they're very far and few people

56
00:08:01,254 --> 00:08:04,298
few and far between, most of us need some sort of support.

57
00:08:04,680 --> 00:08:12,350
And most of us can't get that sort of energy, that what's called samvega, that enthusiasm, that commitment to become enlightened.

58
00:08:12,370 --> 00:08:17,678
You know, most of us would prefer to do little ceremonies and do good and hope we get a better chance in the next life.

59
00:08:19,521 --> 00:08:20,863
So I'm postponing it, you know.

60
00:08:22,146 --> 00:08:27,413
On the understanding that so long as we have to be reborn, there'll always be somewhere to be reborn.

61
00:08:28,154 --> 00:08:28,495
Very interesting.

62
00:08:30,516 --> 00:08:45,313
So apart from those very rare instances where we get these people who can do that, I'm thinking especially of, there was a very famous teacher in Thailand, Ajahn Mun, whom you might have come across.

63
00:08:45,474 --> 00:08:48,697
Have you come across the writings of Mahabua, Ajahn Mahabua?

64
00:08:48,798 --> 00:08:49,658
Have you ever come across that?

65
00:08:50,158 --> 00:08:53,123
So his teacher, you see, Ajahn Mun, seems to have been one of these people.

66
00:08:53,143 --> 00:08:54,725
He just went for it.

67
00:08:54,745 --> 00:08:57,027
He just sat in the forest there in the jungles.

68
00:08:57,447 --> 00:08:58,548
They were jungles then.

69
00:08:59,086 --> 00:09:01,889
and just finally became enlightened.

70
00:09:05,793 --> 00:09:13,520
So, most of us need some sort of structure, some sort of institution to work within.

71
00:09:14,922 --> 00:09:23,990
And if we look at the various rituals, you see that they have a specific role to play in terms of our spiritual practice.

72
00:09:25,352 --> 00:09:28,535
Taking refuge in the Buddha, for instance, when we bow to the Buddha,

73
00:09:29,038 --> 00:09:33,562
What is the body language of bowing?

74
00:09:34,408 --> 00:09:37,142
In the Christian tradition, people kneel.

75
00:09:37,527 --> 00:09:38,508
Muslims bow.

76
00:09:40,270 --> 00:09:42,094
Hindus do all sorts of bows.

77
00:09:42,533 --> 00:09:44,817
What is that body language when you bow?

78
00:09:44,857 --> 00:09:45,599
What does it mean?

79
00:09:45,940 --> 00:09:53,870
It means that you're submitting yourself to the teaching, doesn't it?

80
00:09:54,032 --> 00:09:57,777
It means that whatever the Buddha says, you follow.

81
00:09:57,817 --> 00:09:59,219
It's a submission.

82
00:09:59,480 --> 00:10:02,403
It's getting rid of that ego.

83
00:10:03,110 --> 00:10:04,871
which says, well, I want to do things my way.

84
00:10:05,712 --> 00:10:09,437
The Buddha's right, but I think I've got it slightly better than him.

85
00:10:10,658 --> 00:10:11,899
I don't need to follow him exactly.

86
00:10:11,960 --> 00:10:13,822
I can do it in the way that I want to do it.

87
00:10:14,822 --> 00:10:18,647
I always remember when I first came to Buddhism, I started off in Zen Buddhism.

88
00:10:18,667 --> 00:10:20,489
And in Zen Buddhism, they don't do the full bow.

89
00:10:20,509 --> 00:10:23,552
They just bow from, like Japanese, they just bow from the hip.

90
00:10:24,494 --> 00:10:28,957
And I saw everybody doing this, and I thought, well, this is really weird.

91
00:10:30,159 --> 00:10:33,082
And as I did it, I felt this enormous resistance.

92
00:10:33,163 --> 00:10:41,198
Which is peculiar because I myself have been brought up a Catholic and you always have that sense of, you know, submission.

93
00:10:43,562 --> 00:10:46,629
Doing, in Christian terms, doing the will of God, you see.

94
00:10:47,730 --> 00:10:48,653
But it felt very strange.

95
00:10:48,972 --> 00:10:50,154
And of course it was this ego.

96
00:10:50,174 --> 00:10:51,577
It didn't want to submit itself.

97
00:10:52,182 --> 00:11:03,511
So the bowing, the actual prostration, you see, even that word to prostrate oneself, is a physical act where we express this submission to the Dharma.

98
00:11:04,232 --> 00:11:08,336
Now, with it there has to be this faith, you see.

99
00:11:08,537 --> 00:11:13,422
Now, faith is a kernel virtue that we have to have.

100
00:11:14,523 --> 00:11:20,467
Faith can be understood as an intellectual assent, it's an agreement, it's an understanding that we come to.

101
00:11:21,157 --> 00:11:29,107
many people's progress is undermined by the fact that they can't come to believe entirely what the Buddha says.

102
00:11:29,168 --> 00:11:31,671
So there's always this little level of doubt.

103
00:11:32,392 --> 00:11:34,835
So long as there's doubt, there can't be commitment.

104
00:11:34,855 --> 00:11:36,057
There's always some pulling back.

105
00:11:36,116 --> 00:11:37,999
You can't give yourself 101%, you see.

106
00:11:38,600 --> 00:11:49,914
So, one first of all, you know, reads about the Buddha, or if you're lucky and born into Buddhism, then this faith is something natural in your heart.

107
00:11:50,788 --> 00:12:07,061
In the old days, we used to castigate, we used to look down upon blind faith because it didn't make any sense in a society which more and more believes in scientific investigation, not believing something just because somebody says it's true, the Pope or a Buddhist monk.

108
00:12:07,621 --> 00:12:12,932
The idea is that it has to be proved, you have to have an experiment and prove it's there.

109
00:12:13,957 --> 00:12:22,296
So, in our society we have this idea that blind faith is something which isn't good in itself.

110
00:12:22,797 --> 00:12:28,750
But if you have blind faith in what's absolutely true, then it's an asset, isn't it?

111
00:12:28,769 --> 00:12:33,620
You don't have to go through the problem of trying to convince yourself anymore.

112
00:12:34,023 --> 00:12:35,083
See?

113
00:12:35,104 --> 00:12:42,650
So, in a sense, this is one of the attributes that somebody who's born into the Buddhist understanding has the natural thing.

114
00:12:42,851 --> 00:13:01,789
And if you're not, if you're somebody who's converted to it, or somebody who has slowly come to that understanding, then one has to go through the reading, one has to go through the understanding process, one has to understand the Buddha's teaching, and with it there comes this sense of, you know, this is right, this is meaningful to me, this makes sense to me, you see?

115
00:13:01,809 --> 00:13:03,912
And as that comes, the faith grows, see?

116
00:13:04,886 --> 00:13:10,753
Faith itself, although it has its growth in intellectual understanding, is also a heart thing, isn't it?

117
00:13:10,773 --> 00:13:12,654
It's a sense of commitment.

118
00:13:12,674 --> 00:13:16,198
And with it, of course, there grows this other great virtue, which is hope.

119
00:13:17,440 --> 00:13:26,549
Hope is that heart feeling, that heart state which knows that the Enlightenment will come.

120
00:13:27,971 --> 00:13:31,735
We live in the hope of that eventuality, you see.

121
00:13:31,755 --> 00:13:34,118
Hope is not here to be confused with expectation.

122
00:13:34,570 --> 00:13:36,351
Expectation is hope with a date.

123
00:13:36,971 --> 00:13:40,054
You know, if I begin meditating now, I'll be enlightened in a couple of weeks.

124
00:13:43,878 --> 00:13:49,182
So now this faith that we have has to be expressed.

125
00:13:49,523 --> 00:13:51,244
You know, we have to express it some way.

126
00:13:51,683 --> 00:13:54,586
All our understanding, remember, is always expressed.

127
00:13:54,606 --> 00:13:59,230
It's expressed by the way we speak, by the way we communicate to people, by the way we move.

128
00:13:59,630 --> 00:14:01,152
It's expressed through our personality.

129
00:14:02,352 --> 00:14:04,154
Whether we like it or not, we're all teachers.

130
00:14:04,472 --> 00:14:13,485
As soon as somebody knows you're a Buddhist, then immediately, or at least involved in the Dharma, or a meditator, then they immediately begin to judge you according to that yardstick.

131
00:14:13,504 --> 00:14:16,969
And whether we like it or not, we become teachers to anybody whom we're around.

132
00:14:17,009 --> 00:14:28,083
So, this business of faith, you see, allows us to move into that area of right action, right speech, right livelihood, because

133
00:14:28,402 --> 00:14:38,495
From that faith there comes a conviction that the Buddha's teaching is correct and that somehow I have to re-engage with the world in a slightly different way.

134
00:14:40,264 --> 00:14:59,469
So these rituals that we do, the first one, the simplest one, which is, you know, bowing to the Buddha, bowing to the Dhamma, and then bowing to the Sangha, is this idea of submission, of a sort of contract, a negotiated contract that we have with the Buddha as a living memory.

135
00:15:00,471 --> 00:15:07,099
But it also, of course, has a much deeper spiritual understanding, because when you're bowing to the Buddha, you're really bowing to yourself.

136
00:15:08,563 --> 00:15:10,649
Because it's we, ourselves, that become the Buddhas.

137
00:15:11,270 --> 00:15:20,615
We, ourselves, have become Svakta Buddhas, Buddhas who have followed the Buddha as a way, rather than Sammasambuddhas, Buddhas who have become enlightened by their own particular endeavour.

138
00:15:21,254 --> 00:15:23,878
So there is that, bowing to the Buddha within us.

139
00:15:24,820 --> 00:15:37,119
And that means that we have to listen to this higher voice within us, which is, you know, if we listen carefully enough, it's always guiding us into the skillful path, into the path which leads to our own liberation, because it's there within us.

140
00:15:37,178 --> 00:15:42,267
It's not something, remember, Nibbana or these...

141
00:15:42,246 --> 00:16:11,966
the enlightenment itself is not something which is sort of manufactured it's not something that arrives at the end of a path you know it's like for instance you take a train from London to Manchester and on the way Manchester sort of grows and appears when you get there Manchester is always there so this nirvanic element for want of a better word this buddho the enlightenment is already there within us it's a matter of discovering it discover uncover

142
00:16:12,335 --> 00:16:26,876
See, it's a matter of lifting that consciousness, this paññā, this intuitive intelligence we have, to really discover this new relationship to the world, which the Buddha calls this liberation from suffering, liberation from delusion.

143
00:16:27,798 --> 00:16:29,941
The process of liberating ourselves from delusion.

144
00:16:30,562 --> 00:16:37,211
So that when we bow, it's also an acknowledgement that we ourselves have this Buddha within us.

145
00:16:37,816 --> 00:16:52,634
have the Dhamma within us, have the actual Truth already within our hearts, it's within our minds, it's within our bodies, it's right here, we don't have to go anywhere to get it, we don't have to buy it from somewhere or import it, it's already here.

146
00:16:54,876 --> 00:17:11,301
And the bowing of the Sangha is, you know, in a religious sense, it's accepting that there are people who came after the Buddha who have said that, by their own experience, they also proclaim the enlightenment.

147
00:17:12,103 --> 00:17:15,728
And we ourselves, when we bow, we also join that Sangha.

148
00:17:15,969 --> 00:17:23,500
We may not have achieved any of the noble powers and fruits, but it's there as a potential, you see.

149
00:17:24,374 --> 00:17:35,594
So when we do this bowing, it has a purposeful way of connecting us with our spiritual wealth, with our spiritual essence, which is within us.

150
00:17:39,520 --> 00:17:43,647
Now, we then take the five precepts.

151
00:17:44,506 --> 00:17:53,454
So the five precepts are our basic moral law, just, you know, just at least getting the course level of our behavior to be more refined.

152
00:17:53,836 --> 00:17:58,059
It's the beginning of a refinement of our personalities, you see.

153
00:17:58,079 --> 00:18:04,126
And that again is, you know, we repeat it with the intention of taking them as training rules, right?

154
00:18:04,146 --> 00:18:08,151
They're not commandments, they're not something which, you know,

155
00:18:08,603 --> 00:18:11,730
have some sort of penalty behind them apart from the law of karma.

156
00:18:12,391 --> 00:18:14,655
The idea of punishment isn't necessary.

157
00:18:15,678 --> 00:18:20,689
The law of cause and effect is a good enough teacher.

158
00:18:24,465 --> 00:18:51,519
Various other rituals such as, we don't do it in the West, but in the East things like, you know, bowing to the Bodhi tree, things like that, are all to do with a similar sort of faith, a similar sort of devotion, a similar sort of giving, of emptying oneself for that moment of any ego desires and saying, you know, that I commit myself to this path, you see.

159
00:18:53,473 --> 00:18:57,847
Now, when we come to things like Buddha Rupa, you see,

160
00:18:58,891 --> 00:19:24,257
the actual manifestation of the Dharma in terms of art, in terms of temples, in terms of Buddha-rupa, you see they're all there to sort of create an atmosphere, to create a certain space where we can enter This goes way back in human psychology, you know, the magic circle We need to create a special space where we can go, and it immediately affects us

161
00:19:24,727 --> 00:19:28,353
You walk into a hospital and you walk into an atmosphere.

162
00:19:28,492 --> 00:19:34,682
You walk into a school, you walk into a police station, you know exactly what the atmosphere is there.

163
00:19:35,063 --> 00:19:49,906
So when you walk into a temple or any holy place, there's an atmosphere, there's something about a place, a space, a circle, which allows us to enter into a different mind space, a different way of being in the world.

164
00:19:52,132 --> 00:19:57,758
And the Buddha Rupa itself, you see, I mean, there were no Rupas, as I'm sure you know, for about 500 years.

165
00:19:58,479 --> 00:20:04,405
The first Rupas appeared in the Indian style in Mathura and in the Greek style in Gandhara.

166
00:20:05,205 --> 00:20:08,390
And that's why they had this knobbly little head, by the way.

167
00:20:08,549 --> 00:20:11,173
This was the Greek way of expressing nobility.

168
00:20:11,333 --> 00:20:14,436
They used to curl their hair and put it in a topknot.

169
00:20:14,457 --> 00:20:17,098
So, we've been handed that.

170
00:20:17,160 --> 00:20:21,243
I'm sure the Buddha never quite had that on top of his head, but …

171
00:20:22,000 --> 00:20:35,180
Later on, as you see it develop, for instance, in the later stuff, especially of the tithes, you see that this thing turns into a flame, the flame of enlightenment.

172
00:20:35,240 --> 00:20:39,566
So it becomes very symbolic in that sense.

173
00:20:39,586 --> 00:20:41,709
Now, the root for itself is there.

174
00:20:42,049 --> 00:20:43,152
I mean, what is that?

175
00:20:43,412 --> 00:20:47,518
It's meant to be some sort of image of the enlightened mind.

176
00:20:48,088 --> 00:20:54,460
the composure of it, the silence of the face, the energy in the body posture.

177
00:20:55,201 --> 00:20:57,345
It's all meant to be a teaching thing.

178
00:21:00,990 --> 00:21:03,555
But it was something quite late before that.

179
00:21:03,615 --> 00:21:06,279
The Buddha was represented by the Bodhi tree footsteps.

180
00:21:08,844 --> 00:21:11,868
Various sorts of symbols were used to

181
00:21:12,135 --> 00:21:19,532
to keep in mind for all who came along, in a devotional sense, that the Buddha, the Enlightenment, was somehow right there amongst us.

182
00:21:19,953 --> 00:21:25,487
We didn't have to ... it was a point of reference, you might say.

183
00:21:30,125 --> 00:21:36,853
Now, I'm sure you all saw that scene of the Buddha Rupa being blown up in Afghanistan.

184
00:21:37,614 --> 00:21:38,935
I have to say, it took me by surprise.

185
00:21:39,076 --> 00:21:45,023
I think it was the violence of the explosion, but I felt quite a pain in my heart.

186
00:21:45,064 --> 00:21:52,272
I felt, God, I think I was expecting it just to crumble, but the actual explosion was, I thought, really terrible.

187
00:21:52,292 --> 00:21:54,394
An expression, really, of their anger, wasn't it?

188
00:21:54,575 --> 00:21:56,637
I mean, they're just very angry people.

189
00:21:57,361 --> 00:22:02,786
But in a sense, of course, we don't need any of this.

190
00:22:02,806 --> 00:22:03,547
See, that's the point.

191
00:22:03,968 --> 00:22:09,093
It's not part of our spiritual practice.

192
00:22:09,113 --> 00:22:14,917
This is something that we need because they're little helps, they're little something which lifts us on the path.

193
00:22:15,919 --> 00:22:19,542
They're not absolutely necessary.

194
00:22:19,563 --> 00:22:23,487
So when it comes to these rituals,

195
00:22:24,479 --> 00:22:31,268
They are, shall we say, little entrances, little performances, little entrances to get us into a different frame of mind.

196
00:22:32,250 --> 00:22:37,336
Now, what is that different frame of mind for, you see?

197
00:22:37,817 --> 00:22:39,700
It's to get us into meditation.

198
00:22:40,121 --> 00:22:41,061
And that's the purpose of it.

199
00:22:41,923 --> 00:22:47,631
The bowing is that expression of, you know, I'm now going to obey the Buddha's teaching.

200
00:22:48,011 --> 00:22:49,133
And what is the Buddha's teaching?

201
00:22:49,212 --> 00:22:50,335
The Buddha's teaching is to meditate.

202
00:22:51,428 --> 00:22:59,377
The Buddhist teaching is to practice specifically, not simply meditation, but the way we behave in ordinary daily life.

203
00:22:59,798 --> 00:23:11,152
But it's an entrance into a state of mind which is about turning our lives around and becoming to express the purity of heart.

204
00:23:11,172 --> 00:23:18,059
So, even privately, when we're in our own homes,

205
00:23:18,461 --> 00:23:32,354
you know, to, in the morning, to take the refuges, to bow, to take the refuges, and to take the precepts, as it were, sets us into that frame of mind where we can then sit and begin to do some small meditation.

206
00:23:33,214 --> 00:23:34,976
Now, what is it that the meditation does?

207
00:23:35,457 --> 00:23:38,378
The meditation connects us with what we've just bowed to.

208
00:23:39,621 --> 00:23:40,580
That's the whole point of it.

209
00:23:41,001 --> 00:23:46,967
The whole point of meditation, the whole point of the pasana, is to discover that within us which is the enlightenment.

210
00:23:47,520 --> 00:23:57,109
As soon as we are in a state of good vipassana, we're already beginning to touch upon, we're already beginning to taste the taste of nibbana.

211
00:23:57,130 --> 00:24:02,115
The Buddha says in the Dhammapada, he says, those who are mindful are in the neighborhood of nibbana.

212
00:24:02,736 --> 00:24:05,137
That's how close we are when we're in a meditative state.

213
00:24:08,080 --> 00:24:11,403
Now, if you don't meditate, what's going to happen?

214
00:24:11,704 --> 00:24:12,806
This is the problem, you see.

215
00:24:13,465 --> 00:24:17,190
The problem is if you don't meditate, then what happens to all these rituals, you see?

216
00:24:17,575 --> 00:24:19,156
they start to become empty forms.

217
00:24:21,520 --> 00:24:27,028
There's no meaningfulness to doing that unless there's a movement from the ritual into practice.

218
00:24:27,489 --> 00:24:36,342
The ritual is there simply to create a ground, simply to create an atmosphere within ourselves so that we can then begin to practice.

219
00:24:37,042 --> 00:24:46,317
Now, although I've said, you know, meditation, because I think meditation is a core practice in the sense that, you know, if we can do even 20 minutes in the morning

220
00:24:46,954 --> 00:24:52,144
it sets us, you know, it puts us in contact with that state of mind that we have to carry throughout the day.

221
00:24:52,204 --> 00:25:01,301
I say state of mind, but it's more truthful to say a level of consciousness, a way of being, a way of seeing things.

222
00:25:01,321 --> 00:25:03,546
And from there we go into ordinary daily life

223
00:25:04,116 --> 00:25:29,772
and we connect, we keep trying, even though we lose it throughout the day the sense of mindfulness, the sense of being here the sense of being attentive and careful with what we do, what we say the way we behave, the way we communicate even though we lose it you know, the whole point is to come back, to keep remembering one of the earlier definitions of sati was remembering remembering what?

224
00:25:29,833 --> 00:25:32,757
remembering to, you know, in terms of Buddhism, remembering to be here

225
00:25:33,209 --> 00:25:34,009
Right?

226
00:25:34,029 --> 00:25:36,413
Sati, awareness, mindfulness.

227
00:25:36,433 --> 00:25:38,636
Whenever we're aware, whenever we're mindful, we're here.

228
00:25:38,916 --> 00:25:40,759
You can't be anywhere else if you're mindful.

229
00:25:40,779 --> 00:25:41,760
You're right in the present moment.

230
00:25:42,481 --> 00:25:51,515
So the whole point of the meditation is, in terms of, you know, ordinary daily life, is to keep on connecting us with this center.

231
00:25:52,175 --> 00:25:57,522
And throughout the day, even though we lose it a million times, we keep coming back, we keep coming back, we keep coming back.

232
00:25:57,824 --> 00:25:58,845
Now that's the practice.

233
00:25:59,450 --> 00:26:01,211
That is the practice.

234
00:26:01,271 --> 00:26:10,282
There isn't anything more to it than just that, than just bringing ourselves back into the present moment.

235
00:26:10,303 --> 00:26:13,326
We're establishing mindfulness.

236
00:26:13,346 --> 00:26:19,093
Now, if you don't do that, you see, then what happens to all these rituals and all these performances, you see?

237
00:26:19,614 --> 00:26:27,262
They take on a certain empty quality because they won't have, it won't lead to this meditation which ultimately has an effect on your life.

238
00:26:29,166 --> 00:26:50,237
Even in the Buddhist monastic life, you see, there are certain things that ... very simple things, you know, like putting on the same robes every day in the morning, you know, having to cut your hair off every couple of weeks, or whenever the Society of Monks that you're with do so.

239
00:26:50,678 --> 00:26:57,047
These are all little rituals just to keep reminding the person who is in the monastic order that they've joined the monastic order.

240
00:26:58,224 --> 00:27:02,229
You know, it demands a certain way of behaving, a certain way of speaking, a certain way of being in the world.

241
00:27:03,790 --> 00:27:12,861
And this morning ritual that, you know, really, I think, is necessary for most people who practice in the Dharma.

242
00:27:12,881 --> 00:27:26,036
You know, this idea of just spending a small time in the morning to reconnect with the teaching and to go through that business of committing ourselves to the teaching and then to take the precepts as a basic way of behaving.

243
00:27:26,076 --> 00:27:27,657
You see, all this

244
00:27:27,924 --> 00:27:36,036
is very meaningful so long as there's the effort to live in that state of mind, in the state of the enlightened person.

245
00:27:36,616 --> 00:27:39,099
If you lose that, then these rituals just become empty.

246
00:27:39,339 --> 00:27:47,171
And eventually, because there's no effect from the ritual, there's a great danger that the doubt seeps in.

247
00:27:47,310 --> 00:27:50,935
Before you know it, you basically stop practicing and stop doing the ritual.

248
00:27:51,737 --> 00:27:54,881
So I don't know whether that's clarified a little bit of the situation.

249
00:27:56,042 --> 00:27:57,865
If there's any questions about...

250
00:28:00,628 --> 00:28:07,534
observations, contradictions, I always like a contradiction, criticism, editorials.

251
00:28:10,298 --> 00:28:31,182
Whilst accepting that the rituals give us a framework eventually to be in touch with meditation, nirvana, could you enlighten us how the concept of pancakule evolved and what's the purpose of, I have heard that it's good to give the pancakule when you are alive?

252
00:28:33,505 --> 00:28:36,828
Can you remind me what pancakule is?

253
00:28:36,808 --> 00:28:40,339
That's the one death ritual.

254
00:28:40,359 --> 00:28:41,303
The death ritual, that's right.

255
00:28:41,383 --> 00:28:44,192
Excuse me.

256
00:28:45,556 --> 00:28:48,404
You mean making offerings for the benefit of the dead?

257
00:28:48,907 --> 00:29:18,595
yes and that I have heard the philosophy that it's good to give it if you're when you're alive rather than somebody else offering it at your funeral oh yeah you mean as soon as you're born you do a you do a funeral tradition that's not bad

258
00:29:19,334 --> 00:29:22,857
At least it puts you in a good frame of mind, doesn't it, for the rest of your life.

259
00:29:28,244 --> 00:29:28,746
I don't know.

260
00:29:28,806 --> 00:29:29,386
There's nothing.

261
00:29:29,727 --> 00:29:41,561
You see, all these rituals about doing something for our ancestors and for our forebears, as far as I'm aware, there's nothing of it in the scriptures.

262
00:29:41,682 --> 00:29:45,527
These are something really which are there for the person who's bereaved.

263
00:29:46,704 --> 00:29:57,136
so they feel, you know, that they can do something for the person and in doing so there's a, you know, there's a certain relief in that person, isn't it?

264
00:29:57,678 --> 00:30:13,776
that they can, you know, are offering something of their lives of their benefit to this person who's passed on Now, I think we can presume since the whole universe is interconnected and everything has an effect on everything else

265
00:30:14,161 --> 00:30:19,227
that maybe they do receive these blessings from us.

266
00:30:19,247 --> 00:30:35,346
But I think most of these exercises are much more understandable if you actually see them as practices for ourselves and practices for the healing of our own hearts when they're broken, and for the growth of our hearts.

267
00:30:35,988 --> 00:30:37,890
If you take, for instance, loving-kindness.

268
00:30:38,123 --> 00:30:49,615
Now, we practice loving-kindness, first of all, in the classic tradition of first of all to ourselves, then to those who are near, etc., etc., and then we go out to those who we're indifferent to, and finally to enemies.

269
00:30:50,115 --> 00:31:06,291
Now, I think we can generally believe that, you know, in terms of minds, that we might be connected and that it affects other people when we offer them benefit, you know, even if they live on the other side of the world or in a different realm, yeah?

270
00:31:06,311 --> 00:31:07,894
But what we're really doing

271
00:31:08,126 --> 00:31:10,390
is developing the heart of love within us.

272
00:31:10,690 --> 00:31:13,093
We're developing a different relationship to the world.

273
00:31:13,693 --> 00:31:14,795
And that's what we're really doing.

274
00:31:15,615 --> 00:31:30,574
So that, for instance, when we take that loving-kindness that we might feel quite naturally to those we love, and then we bring to mind people whom we're indifferent to, and eventually enemies, you see, then that love doesn't become bounded by attachments.

275
00:31:33,085 --> 00:31:44,339
The difference, metta, love, is an internal attitude that the Buddha has within his heart which is not dependent on the object.

276
00:31:45,461 --> 00:31:46,844
That's what metta is.

277
00:31:46,864 --> 00:31:51,210
For most of us, unenlightened beings, that love is dependent on whom we see.

278
00:31:52,270 --> 00:31:54,334
You know, we feel more love towards this person

279
00:31:54,532 --> 00:31:57,278
and audible to all these other persons.

280
00:31:57,637 --> 00:32:09,818
So, what we're trying to do is re-educate that heart, transform it, transform those negative states into an inner attitude which is no longer dependent on the world.

281
00:32:10,539 --> 00:32:13,345
It just comes out of that enlightened mind, you see.

282
00:32:13,825 --> 00:32:18,313
Now, that's the, shall we say, the real reason for doing it.

283
00:32:18,833 --> 00:32:42,681
but when we're doing it you can see it does have an effect on us as in the way we behave so for instance it's you know so many people have told me who do the practice that for instance if at work or amongst their family there's someone with whom they've got a big contradiction a lot of aggression and stuff just practicing at least the level of no harm

284
00:32:42,913 --> 00:32:48,499
you see, no harmful response, no backbiting, no response to their hatred or dislike.

285
00:32:49,000 --> 00:32:54,045
That's presuming that they dislike you rather than you dislike them, right?

286
00:32:54,065 --> 00:33:11,942
So, in a situation like that, you see, what happens, you see, by creating this method, by creating this loving-kindness, when you see the person, and remember that human beings are extremely good at recognising people's states from way off, you know,

287
00:33:12,107 --> 00:33:18,815
You can tell, even from a person, I don't know how many yards away, whether they're your friend or not, just by the way they're walking, the look on their face and everything.

288
00:33:19,556 --> 00:33:35,952
So, just going into work, going into that situation where there's aggression towards us, and having established this attitude of no harm, you see, it's already in our posture, it's already in our body language, it's already on our face, which means that the person with aggression has nothing to get hold of.

289
00:33:37,013 --> 00:33:41,659
Anger needs, you know, it needs something to be angry with it, for it to grow.

290
00:33:42,162 --> 00:33:45,445
You know, if anger is just anger, it just fades away if nothing responds.

291
00:33:46,747 --> 00:33:55,717
And so, many people who practice loving-kindness find that these situations of aggression and all that are just dissolved by it, you see.

292
00:33:56,298 --> 00:33:58,319
Now, you can be mystical if you want.

293
00:33:58,339 --> 00:34:07,330
You can think that, you know, this amazing loving-kindness has burst out of your heart every morning and evening towards this audible person, has changed their hearts and all this other stuff.

294
00:34:07,471 --> 00:34:11,275
Or you can believe that just the practice has changed you

295
00:34:11,659 --> 00:34:13,422
And because it's changed you, it's changed them.

296
00:34:13,461 --> 00:34:24,675
Now, in terms of this whole business of death and separation, you know, these are really heavy times for us, aren't they?

297
00:34:24,695 --> 00:34:28,400
You know, we ordinary human beings, we suffer a lot when somebody dies, somebody that we love.

298
00:34:28,621 --> 00:34:30,563
It's a painful, painful situation.

299
00:34:31,164 --> 00:34:32,626
And somehow we need a ritual.

300
00:34:32,686 --> 00:34:35,489
Somehow we need to express that loss.

301
00:34:35,858 --> 00:34:57,597
you know we need to reconnect with the dead person in some way and express all the things that perhaps we also expressed when they were alive and we also expressed when they were alive and to find some way of relieving our hearts of this grief you see now the problem is with great grief of course is this confusion as to what love is so

302
00:34:57,998 --> 00:35:04,927
because we love in an attached way, and it's the attachment, remember, that's caused the pain, not the love, right?

303
00:35:04,947 --> 00:35:07,931
There's a hole in the heart caused by that attachment.

304
00:35:07,952 --> 00:35:15,161
We presume that, you know, if we stop grieving, we therefore stop loving, because the only way we've ever loved is through attachment.

305
00:35:15,882 --> 00:35:21,030
And therefore you can get into this awful downward spiral of going into morbid grief.

306
00:35:21,771 --> 00:35:23,715
Yeah, and then you have to end up on Prozac.

307
00:35:24,655 --> 00:35:26,097
So it's pretty useless.

308
00:35:26,280 --> 00:35:38,273
So, these little rituals, a way in which we human beings can let go, can let go and say, you know, well, whatever I did did any harm to you, you know, I'm trying to make up.

309
00:35:39,375 --> 00:35:39,916
You see what I mean?

310
00:35:40,016 --> 00:35:42,398
It has that sort of, you know.

311
00:35:42,858 --> 00:35:49,947
Now, in terms of the Thai tradition, which I didn't know actually, in a sense, that's what the Buddha is teaching.

312
00:35:50,007 --> 00:35:55,932
I mean, what woke him up, what woke him up out of his, you know,

313
00:35:57,887 --> 00:36:08,860
indulgence in pleasure, in believing that life, you know, the life he was living would just go on forever, which we do, don't we, when we're young, you know, in the twenties, you never think he's going to die, does he?

314
00:36:09,340 --> 00:36:12,525
I know, you know, they're good times.

315
00:36:13,286 --> 00:36:16,889
And then what wakes him up, you see, sickness, old age and death.

316
00:36:16,909 --> 00:36:22,056
That's what he sees, you know, and for him it creates what we would call these days an existential crisis.

317
00:36:22,556 --> 00:36:23,557
He doesn't know what he's living for.

318
00:36:24,313 --> 00:36:29,322
I mean, there he is having a great old time, and suddenly he realizes that he's going to come to an end.

319
00:36:29,742 --> 00:36:32,527
And such was the refinement of his mind that it really hit him hard.

320
00:36:33,748 --> 00:36:41,963
And that's why he goes to the drastic steps of leaving his family in search of some ends of suffering, because he was in touch with that suffering.

321
00:36:41,983 --> 00:36:43,284
He realized he was going to die.

322
00:36:44,311 --> 00:37:00,454
So one of the great meditations that he set for us in the Satipatthana Sutta, the discourse on meditation, on awareness, on establishing awareness, is the meditation, the cemetery meditation, where you observe the body decomposing over its nine stages.

323
00:37:02,697 --> 00:37:05,501
There was an American, you know, who turned up in Sri Lanka.

324
00:37:06,043 --> 00:37:07,164
He was in the newspaper, actually.

325
00:37:07,324 --> 00:37:09,728
Happened before I got there.

326
00:37:10,400 --> 00:37:17,407
I think he was very young in the practice, you know, and he decided to do this practice of watching dead bodies corrode.

327
00:37:17,427 --> 00:37:29,842
Now, what he did was, he got himself a cave, as far as I understand it, and he got himself a cave up in the hill somewhere, and he built himself a glass box with a funnel coming out of it.

328
00:37:29,862 --> 00:37:35,668
And he carried dead body up there to watch it decompose, and it seems that he got permission to do this.

329
00:37:35,688 --> 00:37:37,911
He got a body of a criminal or something.

330
00:37:37,931 --> 00:37:39,072
That was a strange story, yeah.

331
00:37:39,356 --> 00:37:45,815
So he took it up there and began to watch his body decompose, you see, and meditate on it.

332
00:37:45,835 --> 00:37:50,228
And the next thing, the next part, and the newspaper said, now finally, here's a real monk.

333
00:37:50,697 --> 00:37:56,744
You know, he's here to finally, finally we found a real monk who's doing a real meditation watching dead bodies decompose.

334
00:37:57,505 --> 00:38:03,735
And the next part, then the newspapers went dead because he shot off to Calcutta to see Mother Teresa.

335
00:38:04,315 --> 00:38:08,400
I don't know, it was a breakdown probably.

336
00:38:08,782 --> 00:38:10,023
It's a heavy meditation, isn't it?

337
00:38:12,385 --> 00:38:12,806
So...

338
00:38:13,005 --> 00:38:20,802
This constant remembering, this constant reminding us, reminding ourselves that in fact, you know, sickness, old age and death will come.

339
00:38:21,907 --> 00:38:25,141
Old age may not.

